description: Partly from Latin projector (“person who throws away”); partly directly from project +‎ -or.

entries.meaning: Someone who devises or suggests a project; a proposer or planner of something. [from 16th c.]
examples: [A]s the Doctor neither did this, nor yet sent him an answer, the projector wrote a second letter […].

entries.meaning: An optical device that projects a beam of light, especially one used to project an image (or moving images) onto a screen. [from 19th c.]
(psychology) One who projects, or ascribes his/her own feelings to others.
examples: Projectors attempt to get rid of unwanted feelings, only it does not work; they still experience the unwanted feelings  […]

entries.meaning: (mathematics) An operator that forms a projection.
